***I have a drill attachment. Stop telling me to get one 😂 ***
.
How did my business get started? I learned to knit to keep my hands busy. I struggled to focus in classes, but I found if my hands were busy, my mind could focus on listening.
.
A few years later, after moving to a new state, getting married and having no friends, I started making gifts for everyone to save money, and to keep my mind busy. Also, I was now living in Oregon where winters are damp and MISERABLE. I needed more knits 😂
.
Slowly, orders started to roll in from friends and family, so I decided to make it into a side hustle. I started taking custom orders and doing shows around the holidays.
.
Fast forward 10 years, and here we are, knitting full time, and in the Texas heat, to boot 😅
.
Not every hobby should be turned into a business!! I have plenty of things I enjoy doing for fun, and don’t want to monetize them. But my journey was a natural - albeit slow - progression.
.
Yes, I am using a knitting machine. No I do not consider it hand knitted. But I do still consider it handmade because it was made by me, not mass produced ✌🏻
.
How did your handmade business get started? I’d love to hear!

🚨#PSA 🚨 We ALL hate doing it but it’s the easiest (and most common) way to mess up your #WIP. I worked this up for #knitters and #crocheters so no excuses to get it right! Now come on - Check your gauge! (And tag your #friends that need to see this!). So here is how we do it- .
.
1. Create a #foundation row that is slightly longer than the 4in needed to measure. .

2. Work up a #swatch slightly longer than 4in.
.

3. Place a ruler, measuring tape, or this handy #swatch #ruler over the work. Make sure the swatch is laying flat and straight beneath it. .

4. Count your stitches and rows. .

5. Compare to #pattern or #yarn gauge measurements and adjust as needed. Best case, it’s right on and no adjustment needed. Worst case, you need to +/- your #needle or #hook size to get it right. Either way you will #ThankYourself to taking the time to get it right!! .
.
.
